  "opinion": "As a retired woman from Bologna with only a lower secondary education, I’ve seen how stereotypes can quietly shape people’s lives. Stereotype threat in STEM isn’t just about numbers—it’s the weight of fear that makes someone hesitate to try when they’ve already done the work. When I was young, my parents taught me to value effort over innate ability, but back then, the world didn’t always reflect that. Now, I’ve watched my grandchildren grow up in a society that often tells girls they’re not meant for engineering or coding. It’s a quiet erosion, a kind of anxiety that lingers even when you’re trying to do your best. Addressing this isn’t about grand gestures or sweeping changes—it’s about small, consistent actions. For example, when my community center offers workshops for girls in my neighborhood, we focus on storytelling and hands-on projects rather than intimidating technical jargon. We talk about how math and science can solve real problems, like building safer bridges or cleaner water. This approach helps ease the fear of being judged. I’m anxious about the future, but I believe in the power of patience and community. We must create spaces where everyone feels they belong, not just those who fit into a mold. Change starts with listening and then acting—slowly, steadily, without judgment.",
